#limitation(title: [Paediatric Ambulatory Protocols: Limited Trial Evidence for Early Intervention Claims])[
The "early intervention imperative" articulated above is clinically reasonable but rests on indirect evidence:

    - The association between shorter diagnostic delay and better prognosis is observational and subject to confounding (milder cases may be both diagnosed faster and recover more readily, independent of intervention timing).
    - No study has compared early aggressive treatment versus standard care in newly diagnosed paediatric ME/CFS to determine whether early intervention causally improves outcomes.
    - Educational accommodation recommendations are based on expert consensus and disability law, not on controlled studies demonstrating that specific accommodation strategies improve ME/CFS outcomes.
    - The "crash limit rule" and "irreversible crash damage" concepts from patient communities have face validity but have not been quantified or validated by longitudinal studies measuring crash frequency against long-term prognosis.

]
